observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Conduct a thorough review of the corresponding MOAs and engage with the respective source agencies to confirm the validity and intended use of the funds totaling ₱5 million under "Due to NGAs" and ₱22.513 million under "Due to LGUs." If confirmed valid and still intended for project implementation, immediately coordinate with the concerned implementing offices to formulate and enforce detailed project implementation plans with specific timelines to ensure prompt utilization of the funds. Otherwise, if the funds are no longer valid or necessary, promptly return the unutilized amounts to the source agencies in accordance with existing government accounting and auditing regulations;
Initiate the reversion of residual balances and unutilized funds to the source agencies as applicable;
Perform a comprehensive review and validation of the dormant balances. Determine its validity and initiate the necessary documentation for either liquidation or write-off. If the fund is determined to be stale, untraceable, or no longer valid, initiate the refund or write-off process in accordance with the procedures prescribed under COA Circular Nos. 2016-005 and 2023-008, whichever is applicable;
Reclassify the ₱96,984.76 from PHIC for implementation of program by debiting the account “Due to NGAs” and crediting the account “Due to GOCCs”;
Determine the applicable guidelines relative to the fund transfers for prizes amounting ₱25,000.00 from Due to LGUs by coordinating with the respective agencies for proper treatment and reclassification of the funds;
Strictly adhere to Sections 4.6 and 4.9 of COA Circular No. 94-013 by ensuring the preparation of Liquidation Reports on a monthly basis for all received funds, regardless of whether transactions have occurred, and promptly submit within the prescribed period to this Office and the respective Source Agencies. Also, indicate the date prepared, and proper report number in all Liquidation Reports to ensure completeness, traceability, and audit trail integrity. Relative thereto, assign a personnel to monitor the timely submission of the same;
Strengthen financial monitoring mechanisms by conducting periodic reconciliations with Source Agencies to ensure that reported balances are accurate and up to date; and
Require the personnel in-charge in the review and monitoring of commitments and agreements with partner-agencies to clearly specify project implementation timelines, including the start date, completion date, and reporting deadlines, to prevent delays and promote efficient fund utilization. Additionally, ensure that the date of signing by both parties is explicitly indicated in the MOA and notarized. A clear copy of the signed MOA shall be submitted to this Office for proper monitoring and reference.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accounting Office to:
Conduct a thorough review on the outstanding “Guaranty/Security Deposit Payable” account to determine the nature and validity of the balances;
Establish and implement regular monitoring and reconciliation procedures to promptly identify and address long-outstanding balances;
Prepare a JEV to correct the erroneous recording on the proceeds from sale of bid documents totaling to ₱0.649 million by debiting “Guaranty/Security Deposits Payable” and crediting “Trust Liabilities”;
Facilitate the reconciliation of the ₱0.410 million lump-sum beginning balance that cannot be attributed to specific suppliers or contractors, and maintain detailed subsidiary ledgers to ensure accuracy, traceability, and accountability of all transactions recorded under the “Guaranty/Security Deposit Payable” account;
Based on any available historical data (e.g., disbursement vouchers, journal entries, or official receipts) exert efforts to identify the untraceable security deposits and determine whether refunds or write-offs are appropriate; and
Instruct the Municipal Accounting Office and Municipal Treasury Office to formally notify and coordinate with suppliers and contractors with valid claims, requesting them to submit the necessary documents for the prompt processing and release of their warranty and retention deposits.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal HR to immediately update the service records of its employees, utilize the updated service records to reflect the salaries of existing employees in the WEBMSP, and add new/incoming employee transfers in the WEBMSP who were already included in the payroll but not yet in the system;
Direct the Municipal HR, in coordination with the ERF Handler and the Municipal Accountant to review its processes and institute controls and mechanisms to ensure that agency records are up-to-date and membership changes are reflected in appropriate forms and transmitted to the GSIS within the month the information becomes available;
Require the ERF Handler to immediately remit the differential/unremitted premium contributions of employees after the AAO have confirmed that salaries were already updated in the system; and
Direct the AAO and ERF Handler to attend future GSIS seminars in order to equip themselves with the technical capabilities needed for their designation.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to:
Complete the reconciliation of the remaining unremitted balance of ₱0.102 million under the "Due to PhilHealth" account to determine its accuracy and ensure prompt remittance to the PHIC;
Coordinate with the PHIC to validate and reconcile the outstanding premium contributions totaling ₱0.138 million, including the details of the applicable employees, corresponding payroll periods, and supporting documents;
If confirmed to be unpaid, take prompt and appropriate action to settle the outstanding premium contributions, including any applicable interest and penalties, in strict compliance with the provisions of PhilHealth Circular No. 0001, s.2014 and other relevant regulations and issuances; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure proper accounting and disclosure of all outstanding obligations due to PhilHealth in the NFS, in accordance with applicable accounting and financial reporting standards.

We recommended that:
The waterwork service office:
Submit a monthly report on collection and outstanding billings vital for monitoring delinquent concessionaire receivables;
Send demand letters on concessionaires with long-outstanding liabilities providing there for a specific period within which to settle the payables; and
In case of failure to settle, the issuance of disconnection notice shall ensue.
Management establish a written policy manual relative to connection, disconnection, and reconnection to water supply to be reviewed and adopted by the local sanggunian; and
The Sangguniang Bayan:
Review the existing local ordinances on the water system management and update accordingly to conform with the present needs and circumstances;
Conduct an extensive review on the policy manual to be endorsed by the executive department for adoption as warranted; and
Craft an ordinance pertaining to the distribution and control over water meters procured by the agency as this are vital equipment relevant to the management of water supply service in the municipality;

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Engineering Office to conduct, on a timely manner, the detailed engineering activities and Preparation of POWs of Infrastructure projects to preclude the recurrence of non-inclusion of the general components in the indicative PPMP during the Budget Preparation Phase, thereby increasing the CY 20% DF utilization rate at year-end;
Advise the reviewing personnel/bodies including the members of the Sangguniang Bayan to take active participation in rigorously evaluating the propriety, accuracy and completeness of each Department’s budget proposals, to ensure that only relevant, responsive and feasible items are to be funded and implemented out of the 20% DF. Accordingly, all infrastructure projects shall be supported with POWs and DEDs during the presentation of Budget Proposals;
Ensure that all PPAs are meticulously and judiciously planned by rigidly screening PPAs to be funded out of the 20% DF especially during the preparation of budget proposal. Accordingly, require the implementing offices to propose projects that are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready;
Require the BAC and the MPDO to properly plan all its procurement activities, particularly the procurement of infrastructure projects taking into consideration the period of implementation to avoid delays and suspensions;
Advise the MPDO together with the concerned implementing offices, in coordination with the Bids and Awards Committee, to conduct further review of the unimplemented projects under the 20% Development Fund. Formulate/develop specific strategies/solutions to effectively implement development projects;
Direct the implementing offices, to communicate with the regulating agencies to expedite the acquisition of the required clearances. Accordingly, Management shall endeavor to complete all the appropriate preparatory activities such as, but not limited to, cost-benefit analysis, feasibility studies, market research, and detailed engineering designs, regulatory clearances to preclude delays in the implementation of the PPAs; and
Henceforth, intensify the close monitoring of the implementation of PPAs under the 20% DF to attain the desired benefits derived from the implementation of these programs, projects and activities.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Local Disaster Reduction Management Council (LDRRMC) to review the existing PPAs under the LDRRMF to determine the relevance and responsiveness of the projects to the present circumstances including the reasonableness of project costing and make the necessary revisions as warranted subject to the appropriate approvals;
Ensure that PPAs funded out of the DRRM funds are well-planned and meticulously reviewed by the LDRRMC. Accordingly, intensive procurement planning and coordination with stakeholders shall be conducted prior to the inclusion of PPAs in the LDRRMP and LDRRMFIP;
Ensure the utilization of the continuing funds maintained under special trust fund and, if necessary, the LDRRMC perform reprogramming of the unexpended fund into a more attainable PPAs that support disaster risk management activities to further strengthen the municipalities resilience towards disaster; and
Strictly monitor the implementation of the PPAs to facilitate the timely completion thereof but indicating measurable performance indicators.

We recommended the following:
Program/project/activities under the 20% Development Fund identified as investment and long-term assets should be budgeted as capital expenditure;
Record financial transactions in accordance with the Chart of Accounts prescribed under COA Circular 2015-009;
Classify capital expenses as capital assets.

We recommended the following courses of actions:
The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant and General Services Office  with the complete description and cost segregation of road component for road projects;
The GSO or inventory team submit Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network (RPCLRN);
The GSO and Municipal Accountant maintain the required Local Road Network Property and Ledger Cards, respectively.

